key_insights: Support and resistance levels are stronger on higher timeframes (daily, 4-hour, 1-hour) compared to lower timeframes like 1-minute
Use moving averages to confirm horizontal support/resistance levels - when they align, it creates stronger zones
ATR (Average True Range) helps determine logical stop loss placement to avoid getting stopped out prematurely
Always establish CEST before entering a trade: Conditions, Entry, Stop loss, and Target
Draw support/resistance levels first, then turn on moving averages to see if they align for confluence
Psychological round numbers are important levels where the market tends to react
Multiple touches with rejections indicate stronger support/resistance levels
High volume zones combined with pivot highs/lows create more reliable levels
Use ATR to determine if price movement from support to resistance is reasonable within your trading timeframe
Don't overload charts with too many indicators trying to get excessive confirmation - this can cause you to miss entries
If you don't know where you'll exit before entering a trade, you shouldn't take the trade
Market behavior follows patterns similar to human psychology - we are creatures of habit
When looking for building zones with large distances, use Fibonacci to identify middle areas if ATR shows smaller typical moves

notable_events: FOMC day - options premiums make zero sense and create more losers than winners

summary: This is an educational webinar by Bill Fanter and Alberto focused on teaching how to combine support/resistance zones with ATR (Average True Range) for better trade planning and risk management. The presentation emphasizes the importance of identifying strong horizontal support/resistance levels on higher timeframes, using ATR to set logical stop losses, and always having a complete CEST (Conditions, Entry, Stop, Target) plan before entering any trade. The content is conceptual and educational rather than providing specific trade calls.
